post_text: Immediate Opening - K-12 Paraprofessional Position - The Stewartsville C-II School District is seeking a paraprofessional for the greatest small school in Northwest Missouri for the 2020-2021 school year. Interested applicants can find the application on the district website at https://www.stewartsville.k12.mo.us/o/stewartsville-c2/page/employment--502. Applications will be accepted by email. 2020-2021 Registration and Orientation Information

AUGUST 12th
NEW STUDENT REGISTRATION (8:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.)
Please be sure to bring your student’s birth certificate, immunization records, and proof of residency.

post_text: Today marks the conclusion of our COVID-19 meal delivery program. Over the past four months, we have organized, prepared, and delivered over 25,000 meals to families within our community. Had it not been for the commitment of this amazing group of individuals, the task would not have been achieved. So as we conclude the program, please help us in thanking them for stepping up in a time of need, and please remember we as a school community remains committed to helping your families however possible in the weeks and months to come. #TheNest #TheCaridnalWay #CardinalVictory

Pop - Up Mobile Pantry Coming to Stewartsville, MO

Who: Second Harvest Community Food Bank & Stewartsville Food Pantry

What: Pop - Up Mobile Pantry

When: - Friday, June 19, 2020; Starting at 10:00 a.m. – 12:00 p.m. (While Supplies Last)

Where: Stewartsville Food Pantry – 401 Main St. – Stewartsville, MO

Overview: Second Harvest Community Food Bank alongside volunteers will be distributing food through
a one-day mobile food drop in Stewartsville, MO starting at 10:00 a.m. Second Harvest recognizes the
need within this area and is taking action by bringing food to the food insecure individuals in each
respective community. We are all in this TOGETHER!

This program is open to the general public. There are no income guides to utilize this program.

shared_text:
Governor Mike Parson
June 11 at 4:43 PM ·

Pleased to announce that Missouri will fully reopen and enter Phase 2 of its “Show Me Strong Recovery” Plan on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

It is truly incredible to think about how far Missouri has come since March. At that time, no one knew what to expect. There was a lot of uncertainty, worry, and concern. Here we are today, just over 90 days since our first COVID-19 case in Missouri, and I am proud to say we have overcome all of these challenges and more than met our reopen goals.

During Phase 2, there will be no statewide health order. All statewide restrictions will be lifted, though local officials will still have the authority to put further rules, regulations, or ordinances in place.

We must remember that COVID-19 is not gone. It is still extremely important for everyone to continue social distancing. Be proactive. Avoid large, congested crowds, and if you can’t social distance, take extra precautions to protect yourself and those around you.

It is up to us to take responsibility for our own actions.

Governor Parson Announces Missouri Will Fully Reopen, Enter Phase 2 of Recovery Plan on June 16 | Governor Michael L. Parson
Pending expiration of Phase 1 on June 15, Governor Mike Parson announced today that Missouri will fully reopen and enter Phase 2 of its “Show Me Strong Recovery” Plan on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

Governor Parson Announces Missouri Will Fully Reopen, Enter Phase 2 of Recovery Plan on June 16 | Governor Michael L. Parson
Pending expiration of Phase 1 on June 15, Governor Mike Parson announced today that Missouri will fully reopen and enter Phase 2 of its “Show Me Strong Recovery” Plan on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

See more at
governor.mo.gov

shared_text:
Stewartsville Festival
June 11 at 10:23 AM ·

An update for everyone wondering. Due to Covid-19 the planning on the festival was severely halted. We have spoken with the Department of Health, and surrounding communities about their town festivals and are trying to decide about the best avenue to keep everyone safe.

No decisions have been made just yet. We are waiting to see what the Governor says about Phase 2 starting this month. After we have that information we will be better able to make the best decision for out community.

Thank you all for your patience!!

What: Pop - Up Mobile Pantry

When: - Friday, May 29, 2020; Starting at 10:00 a.m. – 12:00 p.m. (While Supplies Last)

Where: Stewartsville Food Pantry – 401 Main St. – Stewartsville, MO

Overview: Second Harvest Community Food Bank alongside volunteers will be distributing food through a one-day mobile food drop in Stewartsville, MO starting at 10:00 a.m. Second Harvest recognizes the need within this area and is taking action by bringing food to the food insecure individuals in each respective community.

We are all in this TOGETHER!

This program is open to the general public. There are no income guides to utilize this program.

post_text:
As you know, the pandemic has affected all of our lives and activities. The Missouri FFA Association is working to find the best solutions within the health concern parameters given by our state and national leaders. During the week of April 20, 2020, they will be releasing videos prepared by the 2019-2020 State FFA Officers announcing Proficiency Award winners (both Area and 1st/2nd state winners), National Chapter Award winners (Gold, Silver, Bronze Emblem categories) and the final four members in each of the four Star State categories (Placement, Agribusiness, Agriscience, and Farmer).
They plan to hold a convention later in the summer (in person or virtual) to focus on recognizing the achievements of FFA members and chapters.
Each evening the week of April 20-24 between 7 and 8 p.m., they release the award videos using Missouri FFA’s Facebook page (@MissouriFFA) and www.missouriffa.org. The videos will also be posted on our Missouri FFA YouTube channel.

Have you completed your CENSUS Questionnaire?
Doing so will help ensure our school and community receive federal funding at the appropriate levels. Not doing so will forfeit our opportunity to a lot of federal dollars.
Households may respond to the Census online (2020census.gov) or by phone (844-330-2020).
The count we get in 2020 will impact the next ten years of federal funding, grants, and other support that utilizes census data.

Stay Safe. Stay Healthy.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g2xalLMrT0s&feature=youtu.be

TOP PRIORITY👊
You might not be aware, but nursing homes have been placed on lockdown and are allowing no visitors which includes no family visiting over the EASTER holiday😩

We want to challenge all of our amazing Cardinal kids to make Easter cards or beautiful spring pictures that can be delivered to local nursing homes. There's a dropbox at Lawsons gas station to drop them in. We will make sure they are delivered before Easter. We also ask that you share photos of each beautiful card or drawings on this post.

Update: Preschool & Kindergarten Roundup - Has Been Moved to MAY 14th

Who: Any student that plans on attending Preschool and Kindergarten for the 2020-2021 school year. Students must be 3-5 years old and potty-trained to meet the guidelines for Preschool. Students must be 5 years old by August 1st, 2020, to meet the guidelines for Kindergarten.

What: Children will be given assessments to determine school readiness, as well as vision, hearing, height, and weight.

When: May 14th, 2020, from 12:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.

Where: School library

What to bring: All incoming students need to bring immunization records, proof of residency, and state-issued birth certificate.

Please email Mr. Stephenson at mstephenson@stewartsville.k12.mo.us to make an appointment. If you have already scheduled an appointment, we will keep the same time that was planned and simply change the date.

On behalf of all of us in ""The Nest,"" THANK YOU

THANK YOU to our parents, grandparents, and caregivers who help to continue providing learning opportunities for our students. We couldn't do it without you!

THANK YOU to our teachers who are putting in countless hours to make sure our students are still provided online and offline learning opportunities, meeting with classes via zoom or google hangout, or answering questions from students or parents. We can't thank you enough!

THANK YOU to our food service staff, Chief Porter and the DeKalb County SRO's who continue to prepare and deliver meals for over 100 of our students daily!

THANK YOU to our community who continue to help us during this challenging time by reaching out, serving warm meals to families, and much more. We are blessed to have such a supportive community!

#TheNest #TheCardinalWay #CardinalVictory

Missouri FFA Association
March 14 at 7:36 PM ·

Ag Ed/FFA Family,
In light of the current health issues and concerns resulting from the coronavirus (COVID-19), the State FFA Convention scheduled for April 23 and 24 is being postponed. Ag Ed staff members are working on a contingency plan for the State Convention program, State Leadership Development and State Career Development Events. My recommendation is that you reconsider holding all area and district FFA events involving significant numbers of students. While a variety of factors go into making a decision like this, be assured that the health and safety of our students and stakeholders is always our primary concern.

As an association we know there will be questions. We are evlauating all options as we move through the next few days and weeks. Continue to check with your advisor and watch social media.

post_text: It’s Dr. Seuss Day at #TheNest! Thank you to all of the parents and grandparents who joined us to make this a special day for our Cardinals!
text: It’s Dr. Seuss Day at #TheNest! Thank you to all of the parents and grandparents who joined us to make this a special day for our Cardinals!

post_text:
Hello Cardinal Families,
In recognition of Read Across America Day and the birthday of the beloved children’s author Dr. Seuss, we would like to invite you to accompany your student to school on March 6th. We will be providing complimentary coffee and donuts from 7:40-8:10 a.m. in the lobby. Normal breakfast options will be available for our students in addition to the donut. You and your student are also welcome to read together during this time in the library. At 8:10, we will have a book reading in the gymnasium.

In order to have a successful morning, please keep in mind:
• Students should have no more than 2 adult visitors – you will not need to check-in at the office as this is a before-school event.
• Classrooms will not be open to visitors.
• Visitors are welcome to accompany their student to the gymnasium for the book reading.
• Visitors will need to leave the building upon the conclusion of the Dr. Seuss book reading.

We look forward to seeing you!

post_text:
Community Blood Drive: March 12, 2020

Why Give Blood?
Community Blood Center must collect almost 600 units of blood daily to meet the needs of area hospital patients. As there is no substitute for blood, we rely on volunteer donors like you to supply the life-saving blood and blood components to hospitals in Kansas and Missouri.

What do I have to do?
Making an appointment is easy! Simply click here and follow the steps below.

Step 1:
Click the link: https://donate.savealifenow.org/donor/schedules/drive_schedule/67981 You will be presented with a list of available blood drives that we sponsor. Select the time most convenient for you.
Step 2:
CBC has a new online Donor Portal. If you have already registered in our former system, you will still need to create a user account for this new system.

If you have not yet created a login in this new system, select the Create One Now option and follow the required fields.

PRESCHOOL & KINDERGARTEN ROUNDUP:

Please call the office to secure your student's screening time. (816)-669-3258

Preschool has a limited number of spots. We will place your student on the preschool list in the order we receive calls to confirm a screening time.

Who: Any student that plans on attending preschool and kindergarten for the 2020-2021 school year. Students must be 3-5 years old and potty-trained to meet the guidelines for Preschool. Students must be 5 years old by August 1st, 2020 to meet the guidelines for Kindergarten.

What: Children will be given assessments to determine school readiness, as well as vision, hearing, height, and weight.

When: April 16th, 2020 from 12:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.

Where: School library

What to bring: All incoming students need to bring immunization records, proof of residency, and state-issued birth certificate.

2 HOUR LATE START INFORMATION:

With the threat of winter weather moving through today and into this evening we want to prepare our families to the possibility of utilizing a late start tomorrow, Thursday, February 13, 2020. *If at all possible the decision to cancel school or implement a 2-hour late start will be made this evening.

What does a 2-hour delay mean?
A delay that causes the school to open two hours later than the normal start time (10:00 a.m.). The school will close at the regular time (3:10 p.m.). The school will not be open for students to enter until (9:30 a.m.). The buses will run regular routes on a two-hour delay.

*Any before-school programs/practices/activities will be canceled.

*Afterschool programs will operate as scheduled.

*Breakfast will not be served.

(Preschool will not be in session on days we utilize a late start.)

Courtwarming 2020 Information

Tomorrow Friday, February 7, 2020, is going to be a great day full of excitement.

In the morning, the cheerleaders will be selling Cardinal tattoos for .50 each. To ensure all our students get one, they will be coming around to each elementary classroom to begin the day.

Cardinal Time: Courtwarming Coronation practice in the gym.

End of Day: Students in grades 7-12 will be dismissed to the gym at 2:20 for Pep Assembly.

KKWK 100.1 FM will be airing both the varsity girls and boys games vs. Osborn. The girls are set to tip-off at 6pm.

During the intermission between the varsity girls and boys, games will be an exciting time for our school as we recognize Gene Saunders with the naming of our basketball court in his honor “Gene Saunders Court.”

During halftime of the boy’s game, the Flag Team will be performing.

2020 Coronation will take place after the boy’s game.

Courtwarming Dance
$2/per student
The Athletic Boosters will be providing pizza and drinks.
The dance will last an hour and a half after the end of the coronation

Good evening Cardinal Families,

School will be in session at “The Nest” on Wednesday, February 5, 2020.

We understand the excitement that is surrounding Kansas City’s Chiefs first Super Bowl parade in 50 years. However, the Stewartsville C2 School District will be open (weather permitting) when the Chiefs hold their celebratory parade tomorrow.

We have made our decision based on what is best for our families as a whole. It is never our intention to create unnecessary stress on families who may lack the work flexibility or child-care availability, except when student and staff safety is of concern.

Thank you for your understanding and patience, and Go Chiefs!

Michael Stephenson
Superintendent

post_text: The Stewartsville C2 Board of Education approved the naming of the school's basketball court after Gene Saunders on Monday, January 27, 2020, during their monthly board meeting. The special dedication ceremony will take place on February 7, 2020, between the varsity girls and boys basketball games vs. Osborn. Gene, better known within "The Nest" as Super Gene, has devoted the past 50+ years of his life as a student, student-athlete, parent, community member, and employee to the Stewartsville C2 School District. Gene has announced his intention to retire at the end of June 2020. A "Gene Saunders Court" logo will be temporarily adhered to the floor until a more permanent one can be affixed at a later date.

post_text:
Happy New Year Cardinals,

It is crazy to think we are now 20 years into the 21st century, but even crazier; we are about to begin the 2nd semester of the 2019-2020 school year. As we return to #TheNest, let’s remember the amazing opportunities we have presented to us daily. We have opportunities to engage in each other’s lives positively, to impact those around us academically, socially, and emotionally. Finally, we have opportunities to decide how we are going to work through trials and tribulations. Interestingly though opportunity by itself does not guarantee success, it only guarantees opportunity. My challenge for each of us as we return to “The Nest” is to seize on our opportunities with 2020 vision and continue to have a mindset that says “Yes I can,” and be prepared to push ourselves to be the best we can be not only for ourselves but most importantly our students. #TheCardinalWay #CardinalVictory

Mr. Stephenson
